arch:property.oc:show_val: A dump layer from space 181. The bones are an even light brown - unlike the more mottled bone from higher levels. There is a fair amount of burning as well as some carnivore gnawing and digestion. Most of the identifiable bones are sheep/goat and there is a fairly good representation of their body parts especially considering the small sample. There is fore limb, hind limb, axial skeleton and teeth. There is also one red deer tooth and a fox mandible and a few pieces of small carnivore jaws. Overall the material looks like post-consumption domestic waste, slightly ravaged by dogs. The assemblage includes three pieces of worked bone - from broken points -and a small amount of turtle, bird, amphibian and small mammal bones. The material was rapidly deposited. Frog and small mammal pulled. An additional dry sieve sample #4 was completely recorded and three flotation samples, #2, #3 and #5 were recorded for diagnostics only. Sample 4 was small and dominated by long bone fragments from sheep sized animals. Both samples #2 and #3 contained huge quantities of frog and and sample #5 contained comparitively little. Sample #5 also contained a few pieces of bird bone. This suggests that the the deposit was not homogeneous and spatial differences within the deposit occurred. However, a significant amount of bone from all samples showed signs of digestion and weathering was minimal. A small amount of fish was also pulled from the flotation samples. The bird in sample #5 could possibly have just come from one creature. The samples seem fairly intensively processed and phalanges tend to be over-represented possibly reflecting this. Overall these samples studied seem to be consistent with those examined earlier and appears to be domestic waste to which carnivores had access. Worked antler object from sample 5 >4mm flotation. Last Number = 253
